    {
      "question": "A quadrilateral $ABCD$ is drawn to circumscribe a circle. Prove that $AB + CD = AD + BC$.",
      "answer": "Using the property that lengths of tangents drawn from an external point to a circle are equal.",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Let the circle touch sides $AB, BC, CD, DA$ at $P, Q, R, S$ respectively.",
          "Since tangents from an external point are equal, $AP=AS, BP=BQ, CR=CQ, DR=DS$.",
          "Summing these: $(AP+BP) + (CR+DR) = (AS+DS) + (BQ+CQ)$.",
          "This simplifies to $AB + CD = AD + BC$."
        ],
        "derivation": "AP=AS, BP=BQ, CR=CQ, DR=DS \\\\ (AP+BP)+(CR+DR) = (AS+DS)+(BQ+CQ) \\\\ AB+CD = AD+BC"
      },
